C0024109.Name: Lung
C0024109.Definition: Either of the pair of organs occupying the cavity of the thorax that effect the aeration of the blood.

C0817096.Name: Chest
C0817096.Definition: The upper part of the trunk between the NECK and the ABDOMEN. It contains the chief organs of the circulatory and respiratory systems. (From Stedman, 25th ed)

C0032225.Name: Pleura
C0032225.Definition: The thin serous membrane enveloping the lungs (LUNG) and lining the THORACIC CAVITY. Pleura consist of two layers, the inner visceral pleura lying next to the pulmonary parenchyma and the outer parietal pleura. Between the two layers is the PLEURAL CAVITY which contains a thin film of liquid.

C0013687.Name: effusion
C0013687.Definition: A collection of fluid in a body cavity, which may be the result of a non-neoplastic disorder (e.g. heart failure) or a tumor (e.g. carcinoma of the lung).

C0029053.Name: Decreased translucency
C0029053.Definition: The quality of being opaque to a degree; the degree to which something reduces the passage of light.

C0175730.Name: biomedical tube device
C0175730.Definition: Any device or component shaped like a hollow cylinder.

C1272706.Name: Interval
C1272706.Definition: A time period, or other type of interval, during which something may be achieved, obtained or observed.

C0032326.Name: Pneumothorax
C0032326.Definition: An accumulation of air or gas in the PLEURAL CAVITY, which may occur spontaneously or as a result of trauma or a pathological process. The gas may also be introduced deliberately during PNEUMOTHORAX, ARTIFICIAL.
Aliases: free air in the chest outside the lung

C0442739.Name: No status change
C0442739.Definition: **Description:**There was (or is to be) no change to the item. This is primarily used when this element has not changed, but other attributes in the instance have changed.

C0205360.Name: Stable status
C0205360.Definition: The quality of being free from change or variation or not taking part readily in chemical change.

C0700321.Name: Small
C0700321.Definition: Limited in number, quantity, magnitude or extent.

C1282910.Name: Upper
C1282910.Definition: In a place or position that is higher.

C0013604.Name: Edema
C0013604.Definition: Abnormal fluid accumulation in TISSUES or body cavities. Most cases of edema are present under the SKIN in SUBCUTANEOUS TISSUE.

C0238767.Name: Bilateral
C0238767.Definition: Affecting both sides of the body or a matched pair of organs.

C0205307.Name: Normal
C0205307.Definition: In pathology, a term that is used to describe a tissue specimen that has a normal appearance.

C0205132.Name: Linear
C0205132.Definition: A mark that is long relative to its width; a length (straight or curved) without breadth or thickness; the trace of a moving point.

C0004144.Name: Atelectasis
C0004144.Definition: Absence of air in the entire or part of a lung, such as an incompletely inflated neonate lung or a collapsed adult lung. Pulmonary atelectasis can be caused by airway obstruction, lung compression, fibrotic contraction, or other factors.
Aliases: partial or complete collapse of part or entire lung

C1705504.Name: KAT5 wt Allele
C1705504.Definition: Human KAT5 wild-type allele is located within 11q13 and is approximately 8 kb in length. This allele, which encodes histone acetyltransferase KAT5 protein, is involved in the acetylation of nucleosomal histones H4 and H2A.

C0018787.Name: Heart
C0018787.Definition: The hollow, muscular organ that maintains the circulation of the blood.

C0085590.Name: catheter device
C0085590.Definition: A flexible, tubular device that is used to carry fluids into or from a blood vessel, hollow organ, or body cavity.

C0449911.Name: View
C0449911.Definition: A specific representation of data, situations, topics, etc.

C0521530.Name: Lung consolidation
C0521530.Definition: A chest X-ray finding indicating the presence of a radio-opaque area in the lung. The opacification is caused by fluid or solid material within the airways or lung parenchyma.

C0178499.Name: Base
C0178499.Definition: A substance that dissociates to give hydroxide ions in aqueous solutions; a substance capable of donating a pair of electrons (to an acid) for the formation of a coordinate covalent bond; a substance whose molecule or ion can combine with a proton (hydrogen ion); a substance that combines with acids to form salts.

C0449468.Name: Volume
C0449468.Definition: The amount of three dimensional space occupied by an object or the capacity of a space or container.

C0025066.Name: Mediastinum
C0025066.Definition: A membrane in the midline of the THORAX of mammals. It separates the lungs between the STERNUM in front and the VERTEBRAL COLUMN behind. It also surrounds the HEART, TRACHEA, ESOPHAGUS, THYMUS, and LYMPH NODES.

C0733755.Name: Positioning Attribute
C0733755.Definition: A reference to the alignment of an object, a particular situation or view of a situation, or the location of an object.

C0392747.Name: Changing
C0392747.Definition: The act of alteration or modification; changed or altered in form or character.

C0205171.Name: Singular
C0205171.Definition: Not accompanied by another or others; exclusive of anyone or anything else.

C0205251.Name: low
C0205251.Definition: A minimum level or position or degree; less than normal in degree, intensity or amount.

C0439801.Name: Limited (extensiveness)
C0439801.Definition: Restricted or in amount, size, or extent.

C0042449.Name: Veins
C0042449.Definition: The vessels carrying blood away from the CAPILLARY BEDS.

C0796494.Name: lobe
C0796494.Definition: A portion of an organ, such as the liver, lung, breast, or brain.

C0262950.Name: Skeletal bone
C0262950.Definition: The structural organ comprised of specialized connective tissue that forms the skeletal components of the body.

C1306645.Name: Plain x-ray
C1306645.Definition: An image produced on a radiosensitive surface by x-ray radiation that has penetrated and passed through a structure.

C0205099.Name: Central
C0205099.Definition: A point or area that is approximately central within some larger region or structure.

C0441587.Name: Clinical act of insertion
C0441587.Definition: The act of putting one thing into another.

C0205123.Name: Coronal (qualifier value)
C0205123.Definition: Of, or related to, or in the direction of the front of the body.

C0005978.Name: Bone Wires
C0005978.Definition: Steel wires, often threaded through the skin, soft tissues, and bone, used to fix broken bones. Kirschner wires or apparatus also includes the application of traction to the healing bones through the wires.

C0205102.Name: Internal
C0205102.Definition: Happening or arising or located within some limits, or especially, within some surface.

C0000768.Name: Congenital Abnormality
C0000768.Definition: Malformations of organs or body parts during development in utero.

C0750502.Name: Significant
C0750502.Definition: A term applied to differences, correlations, cause-and-effect relationships, etc., to indicate that they are noticeable, probably too closely correlated to be attributed to chance and therefore indicating a systematic relation: substantial, fairly large; also having consequence or import, important in effect or meaning. In statistics significant ordinarily indicates a probability of not less than 95 percent, while highly significant indicates a probability of not less than 99 percent.

C0179740.Name: Peripherally inserted central catheter (physical object)
C0179740.Definition: A central venous catheter inserted through a peripheral vein.
Aliases: catheters, vascular, infusion, central venous, peripherally-inserted

C0003483.Name: Aorta
C0003483.Definition: The main trunk of the systemic arteries.

C0205081.Name: Moderate (severity modifier)
C0205081.Definition:
Privacy metadata indicating the level of protection required to safeguard personal and healthcare information, which if disclosed without authorization, would present a moderate risk of harm to an individual's reputation and sense of privacy.

Usage Note:The level of protection afforded moderately confidential information is dictated by privacy policies intended to engender trust in a service provider. May include publicly available information in jurisdictions that restrict uses of that information without the consent of the data subject.

Privacy policies mandating moderate levels of protection, which preempt less protective privacy policies. "Moderate" confidentiality policies differ from and would be preempted by the prevailing privacy policies mandating the normative level of protection for information used in the delivery and management of healthcare.

Confidentiality code total order hierarchy: Moderate (M) is less protective thanV, R, and N*, and subsumes all other protection levels (i.e., *Land *U*).Examples:Includes personal and health information that an individual authorizes to be collected, accessed, used or disclosed to a bank for a health credit card or savings account; to health oversight authorities; to a hospital patient directory; to worker compensation, disability, property and casualty or life insurers; and to personal health record systems, consumer-controlled devices, social media accounts and online Apps; or for marketing purposes

C0185792.Name: Sternotomy (procedure)
C0185792.Definition: Making an incision in the STERNUM.

C0205111.Name: Apical
C0205111.Definition: Relating to or located at the tip (an apex).

C0018800.Name: Cardiomegaly
C0018800.Definition: Enlargement of the HEART, usually indicated by a cardiothoracic ratio above 0.50. Heart enlargement may involve the right, the left, or both HEART VENTRICLES or HEART ATRIA. Cardiomegaly is a nonspecific symptom seen in patients with chronic systolic heart failure (HEART FAILURE) or several forms of CARDIOMYOPATHIES.

C0015252.Name: removal technique
C0015252.Definition: The surgical removal of an organ or a part of an organ.

C0205093.Name: Lateral
C0205093.Definition: Situated at or extending to the side.

C0700364.Name: Appearance
C0700364.Definition: The outward or visible aspect of a person or thing.

C0205178.Name: acute
C0205178.Definition: Having a severe and rapid onset of symptoms with short duration.

C0025080.Name: Medical Devices
C0025080.Definition: Any physical object that is useful for prevention, diagnosis, monitoring, or treatment of disease or other conditions.

C0549183.Name: Midline (qualifier value)
C0549183.Definition: A medial line, especially the medial line or medial plane of the body (or some part of the body).

C0180499.Name: Drain device
C0180499.Definition: Devices designed to establish a channel for the exit of fluids (e.g., air, serum, blood, lymph, bile) or purulent material from a cavity, wound, or infected area. Drains usually consist of flexible, hollow devices (e.g., tubes) with one or more lumina. They are typically made of Silastic, polyvinyl chloride, or, less frequently, rubber; a drain may include a trocar in its lumen. Most drains are used either as components of open drainage systems (i.e., through capillary action and gravity) or in closed systems that usually apply low negative pressure through the drain lumen. Dedicated tubes, catheters, and cannulae are also used for drainage of anatomic sites such as biliary ducts (e.g., T tubes, catheters), the urethra, the stomach (i.e., nasogastric tubes), and the brain ventricle (e.g., hydrocephalus catheters, shunts).

C0694637.Name: Nasogastric Route of Drug Administration
C0694637.Definition: Administration of a drug through the nose and into the stomach, usually by means of a tube.

C0175722.Name: Clip
C0175722.Definition: A small device designed to hold and attach items together.

C0205413.Name: Patchy distribution
C0205413.Definition: Irregular or uneven in quality, texture, or distribution.

C0596790.Name: interstitial
C0596790.Definition: pertaining to or situated between parts of or in the interspaces of a tissue.

C0543467.Name: Operative Surgical Procedures
C0543467.Definition: Operations carried out for the correction of deformities and defects, repair of injuries, and diagnosis and cure of certain diseases. (Taber, 18th ed.).

C0225594.Name: Structure of carina
C0225594.Definition: A ridge or ridge-like structure. In humans it usually refers to the trachea. The carina of trachea is part of the lowest tracheal cartilage which is placed between the orifices of the two bronchi.
Aliases: structure of carina of trachea (body structure)

C0205219.Name: Diffuse
C0205219.Definition: Widely spread; not localized or confined.

C0439739.Name: Reticular
C0439739.Definition: Applies to an abnormality whose distribution and appearance resembles a net or network-like structure. []

C0678594.Name: Structure
C0678594.Definition: The components and their relationship and manner of arrangement in constituting a whole.

C0035561.Name: Bone structure of rib
C0035561.Definition: A set of twelve curved bones which connect to the vertebral column posteriorly, and terminate anteriorly as costal cartilage. Together, they form a protective cage around the internal thoracic organs.

C0016658.Name: Fracture
C0016658.Definition: A traumatic injury to the bone in which the continuity of the bone is broken.

C0205143.Name: Angular
C0205143.Definition: The inclination of one line to another or the plane of one object to another.

C0677535.Name: Walls of a building
C0677535.Definition: A layer of material that encloses space or that encloses a structure.

C1521721.Name: Supportive assistance
C1521721.Definition: Moral, psychological, physical, or financial aid or assistance; approval.

C0439064.Name: Numerous
C0439064.Definition: An indefinite large quantity that is considered to be greater than several.

C0542339.Name: Inferior
C0542339.Definition: In a place or position that is lower.

C0005847.Name: Blood Vessel
C0005847.Definition: Any of the tubular vessels conveying the blood (arteries, arterioles, capillaries, venules, and veins).

C1710706.Name: Zone
C1710706.Definition: An area or region distinguished from adjacent parts by a distinctive feature or characteristic.

C0234621.Name: Visual
C0234621.Definition: Relating to or using sight; able to be seen.

C0549177.Name: Large
C0549177.Definition: Of considerable or relatively great size, extent, or capacity.

C0392756.Name: Reduced
C0392756.Definition: Made less in size or amount or degree.

C0031809.Name: Physical Examination
C0031809.Definition: Systematic and thorough inspection of the patient for physical signs of disease or abnormality.

C0205147.Name: regional
C0205147.Definition: Of or belonging to a broader area or region of the body.

C0040300.Name: Body tissue
C0040300.Definition: Collections of differentiated CELLS, such as EPITHELIUM; CONNECTIVE TISSUE; MUSCLES; and NERVE TISSUE. Tissues are cooperatively arranged to form organs with specialized functions such as RESPIRATION; DIGESTION; REPRODUCTION; MOVEMENT; and others.

C0018792.Name: Heart Atrium
C0018792.Definition: The chambers of the heart, to which the BLOOD returns from the circulation.

C0447122.Name: Structure of vein of trunk
C0447122.Definition: Tubular organ part, the wall and lumen of which are continuous with those of the atria of the heart, directly or indirectly through tributaries of the venae cavae, pulmonary veins and the hepatic and portal veins. Examples: coronary sinus, posterior intercostal vein, hepatic vein, bronchial vein, pulmonary vein, trunk of inferior vena cava.
Aliases: structure of vein of trunk (body structure)

C0547040.Name: Minimal
C0547040.Definition: Description:Provides more than identified, but not as much as universal. There are not expected to be many of these.

C0205108.Name: Distal (qualifier value)
C0205108.Definition: Situated farthest from a point of attachment or origin, as of a limb or bone; or directed away from the midline of the body.

C0015385.Name: Limb structure
C0015385.Definition: The farthest or outermost projections of the body, such as the HAND and FOOT.

C0003842.Name: Arteries
C0003842.Definition: The vessels carrying blood away from the heart.

C0302908.Name: Liquid substance
C0302908.Definition: A substance in the fluid state of matter having no fixed shape but a fixed volume.

C1883067.Name: Space - property
C1883067.Definition: An empty area; an area set apart or available for use.

C0810633.Name: Pacemakers
C0810633.Definition: Stimulators used to regulate or substitute the normal rate at which a biologic center establishes the regular intervals of activity (rhythm) of an organ (e.g., heart, lungs). These stimulators control the pace by means of some artificial (e.g., electric generator) stimuli. Pacemakers can be designed either for continuous use (usually implantable devices) or for temporary external use.

C0009450.Name: Communicable Diseases
C0009450.Definition: An illness caused by an infectious agent or its toxins that occurs through the direct or indirect transmission of the infectious agent or its products from an infected individual or via an animal, vector or the inanimate environment to a susceptible animal or human host.

C0012634.Name: Disease
C0012634.Definition: A definite pathologic process with a characteristic set of signs and symptoms. It may affect the whole body or any of its parts, and its etiology, pathology, and prognosis may be known or unknown.
Aliases: clinical disease or syndrome present, nos

C0038351.Name: Stomach
C0038351.Definition: An organ of digestion situated in the left upper quadrant of the abdomen between the termination of the ESOPHAGUS and the beginning of the DUODENUM.

C0013990.Name: Pathological accumulation of air in tissues
C0013990.Definition: A pathological accumulation of air in tissues or organs.
Aliases: pathological accumulation of air in tissues
abnormal collection of air in tissues

C0332232.Name: Approximate
C0332232.Definition: Not quite exact or correct; almost exact or correct.

C0205400.Name: Thickened
C0205400.Definition: An increase in the thickness of a structure.

C0032285.Name: Pneumonia
C0032285.Definition: Infection of the lung often accompanied by inflammation.

C0332290.Name: Consistent with
C0332290.Definition: Marked by a reasonable or logical relation of parts and holding together as a harmonious or credible whole.

C1704258.Name: Abnormality
C1704258.Definition: A condition that differs from the usual physical or mental state.

C0522015.Name: Upright
C0522015.Definition: In a vertical position or posture.

C0439794.Name: Dense
C0439794.Definition: Having high relative density or specific gravity; permitting little if any light to pass through.

C0006660.Name: Physiologic calcification
C0006660.Definition: Process by which organic tissue becomes hardened by the physiologic deposit of calcium salts.

C0205358.Name: Soft
C0205358.Definition: Lacking in hardness relatively or comparatively.

C0849355.Name: Removed
C0849355.Definition: Taken out of, separated from, or eliminated.

C0040578.Name: Trachea
C0040578.Definition: The cartilaginous and membranous tube descending from the larynx and branching into the right and left main bronchi.

C1522410.Name: Highest
C1522410.Definition: Approaching or constituting a maximum; the highest point (of something).

C0178587.Name: density
C0178587.Definition: The amount of something per unit size.

C0038846.Name: Supine Position
C0038846.Definition: The posture of an individual lying face up.

C0205095.Name: Dorsal
C0205095.Definition: Pertaining to the back or upper surface of the body; opposite of ventral.

C0008767.Name: Cicatrization
C0008767.Definition: The formation of fibrous tissue in the place of normal tissue during the process of WOUND HEALING. It includes scar tissue formation occurring in healing internal organs as well as in the skin after surface injuries.

C0018827.Name: Heart Ventricle
C0018827.Definition: The lower right and left chambers of the heart. The right ventricle pumps venous BLOOD into the LUNGS and the left ventricle pumps oxygenated blood into the systemic arterial circulation.

C0449774.Name: Patterns
C0449774.Definition: An arrangement of objects, facts, behaviors, or other things which have scientific, mathematical, geometric, statistical, or other meaning.

C0227952.Name: Foreskin of penis
C0227952.Definition: The double-layered skin fold that covers the GLANS PENIS, the head of the penis.

C0038293.Name: Sternum
C0038293.Definition: A long, narrow, and flat bone commonly known as BREASTBONE occurring in the midsection of the anterior thoracic segment or chest region, which stabilizes the rib cage and serves as the point of origin for several muscles that move the arms, head, and neck.

C0230168.Name: Abdominal Cavity
C0230168.Definition: The region in the abdomen extending from the thoracic DIAPHRAGM to the plane of the superior pelvic aperture (pelvic inlet). The abdominal cavity contains the PERITONEUM and abdominal VISCERA, as well as the extraperitoneal space which includes the RETROPERITONEAL SPACE.

C0027530.Name: Neck
C0027530.Definition: The part of a human or animal body connecting the HEAD to the rest of the body.

C0876954.Name: Contour form
C0876954.Definition: The outline of a part; the surface configuration.

C0449830.Name: With configuration
C0449830.Definition: The spatial property of the way in which something is placed.

C0038969.Name: Surgical sutures
C0038969.Definition: Materials used in closing a surgical or traumatic wound. (From Dorland, 28th ed)

C0011980.Name: Respiratory Diaphragm
C0011980.Definition: The musculofibrous partition that separates the THORACIC CAVITY from the ABDOMINAL CAVITY. Contraction of the diaphragm increases the volume of the thoracic cavity aiding INHALATION.

C0205284.Name: Marginal
C0205284.Definition: A boundary line or the area immediately inside the boundary.

C0028259.Name: Nodule
C0028259.Definition: A small lump, swelling or collection of tissue.

C0582103.Name: Medical Examination
C0582103.Definition: An appraisal or evaluation of a patient's condition by a clinician that is based on a physical exam, medical history, and the patient's account of symptoms.

C0040590.Name: Tracheostomy procedure
C0040590.Definition: Surgical formation of an opening into the trachea through the neck, or the opening so created.

C0008913.Name: Bone structure of clavicle
C0008913.Definition: A bone on the ventral side of the shoulder girdle, which in humans is commonly called the collar bone.

C0205094.Name: Anterior
C0205094.Definition: Of or involving the front of a main body.

C0332448.Name: Infiltration
C0332448.Definition: The process of the diffusion or accumulation in a tissue or cells of a substance not normal to it or in amounts above normal. (NCI)

C3470541.Name: RUBCNL gene
Aliases: run and cysteine rich domain containing beclin 1 interacting protein like

C0332835.Name: Transplanted tissue
C0332835.Definition: Organs, tissues, or cells taken from the body for grafting into another area of the same body or into another individual.

C0577559.Name: Mass of body structure
C0577559.Definition: A benign or malignant pathologic structure in any part of the body, resulting from a neoplastic accumulation of cells, inflammatory cells, or cystic changes.

C0549207.Name: Bone structure of spine
C0549207.Definition: Any of the ring-shaped bony structures that constitute the spinal column and surround the spinal cord.

C0242821.Name: Human body
C0242821.Definition: The human being as a non-anatomical and non-zoological entity. The emphasis is on the philosophical or artistic treatment of the human being, and includes lay and social attitudes toward the body in history. (From J. Cassedy, NLM History of Medicine Division)

C0205107.Name: Proximal
C0205107.Definition: Situated nearest to a point of attachment or origin.

C1517945.Name: Loss
C1517945.Definition: A gradual decline in amount or activity.

C0933845.Name: Parenchyma
C0933845.Definition: The tissue that constitutes the essential part of an organ as contrasted with e.g., connective tissue and blood vessels.

C0441889.Name: Levels (qualifier value)
C0441889.Definition: A position on a scale measuring intensity, quality, or amount.

C0205191.Name: chronic
C0205191.Definition: Usually used to describe a condition that is persistent and long standing.

C0230467.Name: Arch of foot
C0230467.Definition: arch shaped bony structure of the foot
Aliases: structure of arch of foot (body structure)

C0205082.Name: Severe (severity modifier)
C0205082.Definition: Intensely bad or unpleasant in degree, quality or extent.

C0004454.Name: Axilla
C0004454.Definition: Area of the human body underneath the SHOULDER JOINT, also known as the armpit or underarm.

C0205225.Name: Primary
C0205225.Definition: Occurring first in time or sequence; original; of greatest rank or importance or value.

C1514893.Name: physiologic resolution
C1514893.Definition: Return to the normal structure and/or function, e.g. the subsidence of a pathologic process, as the subsidence of an inflammatory lesion or new growth.

C0446516.Name: Upper arm
C0446516.Definition: The superior part of the upper extremity between the SHOULDER and the ELBOW.
Aliases: structure of upper extremity between shoulder and elbow
structure of upper extremity between shoulder and elbow (body structure)
proximal segment of free upper limb

C1265611.Name: Quantity
C1265611.Definition: How much there is of something that you can measure; the total amount or number.

C0038257.Name: Stent, device
C0038257.Definition: Devices that provide support for tubular structures that are being anastomosed or for body cavities during skin grafting.

C0205231.Name: Extensive
C0205231.Definition: Large in quantity, range, or spatial extent.

C0934502.Name: anatomical layer
C0934502.Definition: A relatively thin sheetlike expanse or region lying over or under another.

C0220825.Name: Evaluation
C0220825.Definition: Systematic, objective appraisal of the significance, effectiveness, and impact of activities or condition according to specified objectives and criteria.

C0029453.Name: Osteopenia
C0029453.Definition: Decreased calcification or density of bone tissue.

C0037004.Name: Shoulder
C0037004.Definition: Part of the body in humans and primates where the arms connect to the trunk. The shoulder has five joints; ACROMIOCLAVICULAR joint, CORACOCLAVICULAR joint, GLENOHUMERAL joint, scapulathoracic joint, and STERNOCLAVICULAR joint.

C1523994.Name: Diagnostic, Therapeutic, and Research Equipment
C1523994.Definition: A manufactured object that is used to perform diagnostic, therapeutic or research activities.

C0205194.Name: Coarse
C0205194.Definition: Composed of relatively large parts or particles.

C0033204.Name: Probability
C0033204.Definition: The study of chance processes or the relative frequency characterizing a chance process.

C1440080.Name: Alveolar
C1440080.Definition: Of or relating to the alveoli.

C0449438.Name: Status
C0449438.Definition: A condition or state at a particular time.

C0205150.Name: Hilar
C0205150.Definition: Refers to the area associated with the hilum.

C0017446.Name: Geographic Locations
C0017446.Definition: The continents and countries situated on those continents; the UNITED STATES and each of the constituent states arranged by region; CANADA and each of its provinces; AUSTRALIA and each of its states; the major bodies of water and major islands on both hemispheres; and selected major cities.

C0020564.Name: Hypertrophy
C0020564.Definition: General increase in bulk of a part or organ due to CELL ENLARGEMENT and accumulation of FLUIDS AND SECRETIONS, not due to tumor formation, nor to an increase in the number of cells (HYPERPLASIA).

C0439792.Name: Extent
C0439792.Definition: The range, magnitude, or distance over which a thing spans an interval of distance, space, or time.

C0547044.Name: Smaller
C0547044.Definition: Of lower rank, degree, or importance; of reduced size, extent, or degree; more limited in quantity.

C0524724.Name: Staple, Surgical
C0524724.Definition: Small pieces of thin metallic wires, typically U-shaped, that are appropriate for mechanically fastening tissues together. Most staples are made of stainless, non-absorbable, biocompatible metals (e.g., stainless steel, chromium, titanium) or metallic alloys; they are available in several different shapes and calibers according to the intended use (e.g., bone, vessel, skin). Staples are used in surgery to join many types of organs and tissues, especially in the anastomosis of tubular structures such as the gastrointestinal tract and vasculature; other staples are used for skin wound closure. Most staples are delivered using dedicated instruments (e.g., staplers, drivers). Stapling is generally faster and produces less tissue trauma than standard suturing techniques.

C0205101.Name: Extrinsic
C0205101.Definition: Happening or arising or located outside or beyond some limits, or especially, some surface.

C0332469.Name: Fissure
C0332469.Definition: A long narrow slit or groove that divides an organ into lobes.

C0205098.Name: Medial
C0205098.Definition: Toward the middle or inside (as opposed to lateral).

C0205197.Name: Complete
C0205197.Definition: To possess every necessary or normal part or component or step; having come or been brought to a conclusion.

C0022417.Name: Joints
C0022417.Definition: Also known as articulations, these are points of connection between the ends of certain separate bones, or where the borders of other bones are juxtaposed.

C0332464.Name: Widening
C0332464.Definition: Very large in expanse or scope; having great extent from one side to the other.

C0333482.Name: atherosclerotic
C0333482.Definition: status similar or related to atherosclerosis

C0929176.Name: Hilum
C0929176.Definition: A depression or fissure where vessels or nerves or ducts enter a bodily organ.

C1279919.Name: Early
C1279919.Definition: At or near the beginning of a period of time or course of events.

C0205250.Name: High
C0205250.Definition: An elevated level or position or degree; greater than normal in degree or intensity or amount.

C0021925.Name: Intubation (procedure)
C0021925.Definition: Introduction of a tube into a hollow organ to restore or maintain patency if obstructed. It is differentiated from CATHETERIZATION in that the insertion of a catheter is usually performed for the introducing or withdrawing of fluids from the body.

C0012359.Name: Pathological Dilatation
C0012359.Definition: The condition of an anatomical structure's being dilated beyond normal dimensions.

C0026193.Name: Minor (person)
C0026193.Definition: A person who has not attained the age at which full civil rights are accorded.

C0017110.Name: Gases
C0017110.Definition: The vapor state of matter; nonelastic fluids in which the molecules are in free movement and their mean positions far apart. Gases tend to expand indefinitely, to diffuse and mix readily with other gases, to have definite relations of volume, temperature, and pressure, and to condense or liquefy at low temperatures or under sufficient pressure. (Grant & Hackh's Chemical Dictionary, 5th ed)

C0020164.Name: Bone structure of humerus
C0020164.Definition: Bone in humans and primates extending from the SHOULDER JOINT to the ELBOW JOINT.

C0010383.Name: Crowding
C0010383.Definition: An excessive number of individuals, human or animal, in relation to available space.

C0746591.Name: mitral
C0746591.Definition: a valve that controls blood flow between heart chambers

C0449851.Name: Techniques
C0449851.Definition: A practiced and regimented skill or series of actions.

C0221198.Name: Lesion
C0221198.Definition: A localized pathological or traumatic structural change, damage, deformity, or discontinuity of tissue, organ, or body part.

C0005910.Name: Body Weight
C0005910.Definition: The mass or quantity of heaviness of an individual. It is expressed by units of pounds or kilograms.

C0441987.Name: Side
C0441987.Definition: A line segment forming part of the perimeter of a plane figure.

C0014876.Name: Esophagus
C0014876.Definition: The muscular membranous segment between the PHARYNX and the STOMACH in the UPPER GASTROINTESTINAL TRACT.

C1521738.Name: Field
C1521738.Definition: An area of database record, or graphical user interface form, into which a particular item of data is entered.

C0520510.Name: Materials
C0520510.Definition: The tangible substance that goes into the makeup of a physical object.

C0750729.Name: Course
C0750729.Definition: Passage through time; duration; a systematic or/and orderly succession; a sequence, e.g. course of treatment; a mode of action or behavior; natural development, typical manner of proceeding.

C0553534.Name: Cardiopulmonary
C0553534.Definition: Pertaining to both the heart and the lungs.

C0556030.Name: Repositioning (procedure)
C0556030.Definition: The act of placing in a new position.

C1304890.Name: Enteral
C1304890.Definition: An intended site for a dose form that is for administration to the gastrointestinal tract.

C0020303.Name: Hydropneumothorax
C0020303.Definition: A collection of fluid and gas within the pleural cavity. (Dorland, 27th ed)

C0006282.Name: Contrast bronchogram
C0006282.Definition: Radiography of the bronchial tree after injection of a contrast medium.

C0549178.Name: Continuous
C0549178.Definition: Remain in force or carry on without letup; keep or maintain in unaltered condition; exist in time or space without stop or interruption.

C0521116.Name: Current (present time)
C0521116.Definition: Occurring in or belonging to the present time.

C0019664.Name: History
C0019664.Definition: Record and study of past events.

C0728938.Name: Partial
C0728938.Definition: Being or affecting only a part of something.

C0030705.Name: Patients
C0030705.Definition: Individuals participating in the health care system for the purpose of receiving therapeutic, diagnostic, or preventive procedures.

C0011945.Name: Physical Dialysis
C0011945.Definition: A process of selective diffusion through a membrane. It is usually used to separate low-molecular-weight solutes which diffuse through the membrane from the colloidal and high-molecular-weight solutes which do not. (McGraw-Hill Dictionary of Scientific and Technical Terms, 4th ed)

C0450429.Name: Location
C0450429.Definition: A position, site, or point in space where something can be found.

C0521329.Name: Spinal
C0521329.Definition: Of or relating to the spine or spinal cord.

C0520453.Name: Cannula device
C0520453.Definition: Short, hollow cylinders or tubes for insertion into a canal, vessel, or body cavity.

C0021853.Name: Intestines
C0021853.Definition: The section of the alimentary canal from the STOMACH to the ANAL CANAL. It includes the LARGE INTESTINE and SMALL INTESTINE.

C0205161.Name: Abnormal
C0205161.Definition: Deviating in any way from the state, position, structure, condition, behavior, or rule which is considered a norm.

C0180307.Name: Defibrillators
C0180307.Definition: Cardiac electrical stimulators that apply brief high-voltage electroshocks to the HEART. These stimulators are used to restore normal rhythm and contractile function in hearts of patients who are experiencing VENTRICULAR FIBRILLATION or ventricular tachycardia (TACHYCARDIA, VENTRICULAR) that is not accompanied by a palpable PULSE. Some defibrillators may also be used to correct certain noncritical dysrhythmias (called synchronized defibrillation or CARDIOVERSION), using relatively low-level discharges synchronized to the patient's ECG waveform. (UMDNS, 2003)

C0497156.Name: Lymphadenopathy
C0497156.Definition: An enlarged lymph node. Causes include viral and bacterial infections and cancers that affect the lymph nodes.

C0449719.Name: Part
C0449719.Definition: One of the portions into which something is regarded as divided and which together constitute a whole.

C0018670.Name: Head
C0018670.Definition: The upper part of the human body, or the front or upper part of the body of an animal, typically separated from the rest of the body by a neck, and containing the brain, mouth, and sense organs.

C0553891.Name: Tracheal Extubation
C0553891.Definition: The removal of a previously inserted tube from a hollow organ or passageway, often from the airway.

C0016538.Name: Projections and Predictions
C0016538.Definition: The prediction or projection of the nature of future problems or existing conditions based upon the extrapolation or interpretation of existing scientific data or by the application of scientific methodology.

C0205100.Name: Peripheral
C0205100.Definition: On or near an edge or constituting an outer boundary; the outer area.

C0018188.Name: Granuloma
C0018188.Definition: A relatively small nodular inflammatory lesion containing grouped mononuclear phagocytes, caused by infectious and noninfectious agents.

C0031050.Name: Pericardial sac structure
C0031050.Definition: A conical fibro-serous sac surrounding the HEART and the roots of the great vessels (AORTA; VENAE CAVAE; PULMONARY ARTERY). Pericardium consists of two sacs: the outer fibrous pericardium and the inner serous pericardium. The latter consists of an outer parietal layer facing the fibrous pericardium, and an inner visceral layer (epicardium) resting next to the heart, and a pericardial cavity between these two layers.

C0025062.Name: Mediastinal Emphysema
C0025062.Definition: Presence of air in the mediastinal tissues due to leakage of air from the tracheobronchial tree, usually as a result of trauma.

C0332514.Name: Asymmetry (qualifier value)
C0332514.Definition: A finding of a lack of symmetry between two or more bilaterally aligned structures.

C0000726.Name: Abdomen
C0000726.Definition: That portion of the body that lies between the THORAX and the PELVIS.
Aliases: structure of abdominopelvic cavity and/or content of abdominopelvic cavity and/or anterior abdominal wall (body structure)
intra-abdominopelvic structure and/or anterior abdominal wall
structure of abdominopelvic cavity and/or content of abdominopelvic cavity and/or anterior abdominal wall

C0036974.Name: Shock
C0036974.Definition: A pathological condition manifested by failure to perfuse or oxygenate vital organs.

C0700124.Name: Dilated
C0700124.Definition: The condition of being dilated or stretched.

C0035139.Name: Surgical Replantation
C0035139.Definition: Restoration of an organ or other structure to its original site.

C0006255.Name: Bronchi
C0006255.Definition: The larger air passages of the lungs arising from the terminal bifurcation of the TRACHEA. They include the largest two primary bronchi which branch out into secondary bronchi, and tertiary bronchi which extend into BRONCHIOLES and PULMONARY ALVEOLI.

C0205210.Name: Clinical
C0205210.Definition: Relating to the examination and treatment of patients dependent on direct observation. The term may also refer to the institution (clinic) providing this activity.

C1708612.Name: Knob Device
C1708612.Definition: A handle, usually attached to a shaft allowing manual rotation of the shaft.

C0018896.Name: Helping Behavior
C0018896.Definition: Behaviors associated with the giving of assistance or aid to individuals.

C0032790.Name: Postoperative Period
C0032790.Definition: The period following a surgical operation.

C1516698.Name: Collection (action)
C1516698.Definition: The act of gathering things together; having been brought together in one place.

C0016059.Name: Fibrosis
C0016059.Definition: Any pathological condition where fibrous connective tissue invades any organ, usually as a consequence of inflammation or other injury.
Aliases: fibrosis (formation of excess fibrous connective tissue)

C0026597.Name: Motion
C0026597.Definition: Physical motion, i.e., a change in position of a body or subject as a result of an external force. It is distinguished from MOVEMENT, a process resulting from biological activity.

C0175649.Name: Prosthesis
C0175649.Definition: A device which is an artificial substitute for a missing body part or function; used for functional or cosmetic reasons, or both.

C0011127.Name: Pressure Ulcer
C0011127.Definition: Death of tissue due to external pressure.

C1707455.Name: Comparison
C1707455.Definition: The examination of two or more people or things in order to detect similarities and differences.

C0019270.Name: Hernia
C0019270.Definition: Protrusion of tissue, structure, or part of an organ through the bone, muscular tissue, or the membrane by which it is normally contained. Hernia may involve tissues such as the ABDOMINAL WALL or the respiratory DIAPHRAGM. Hernias may be internal, external, congenital, or acquired.

C0024090.Name: Lumbar Region
C0024090.Definition: The region of the spine below the ribs and above the hipbones.
Aliases: posterior wall of abdominal proper segment of trunk
structure of lumbar region of back (body structure)
structure of lumbar region of back

C0006267.Name: Bronchiectasis
C0006267.Definition: Persistent abnormal dilatation of the bronchi.
Aliases: permanent enlargement of the airways of the lungs
chronic dilatation of bronchus and bronchiole

C0449445.Name: Approach (spatial)
C0449445.Definition: A way of entering or leaving.

C0006141.Name: Breast
C0006141.Definition: In humans, one of the paired regions in the anterior portion of the THORAX. The breasts consist of the MAMMARY GLANDS, the SKIN, the MUSCLES, the ADIPOSE TISSUE, and the CONNECTIVE TISSUES.

C0039991.Name: Thoracotomy
C0039991.Definition: Surgical incision into the chest wall.

C0036439.Name: Scoliosis, unspecified
C0036439.Definition: An appreciable lateral deviation in the normally straight vertical line of the spine. (Dorland, 27th ed)

C0205189.Name: Borderline
C0205189.Definition: Straddling the dividing line between two categories.

C0182537.Name: pump (device)
C0182537.Definition: A device designed to facilitate the movement of a fluid.

C0009938.Name: Contusions
C0009938.Definition: Injuries resulting in hemorrhage, usually manifested in the skin.

C0441633.Name: Scanning
C0441633.Definition: The data or image obtained by gathering information with a sensing device.

C0205249.Name: Healed
C0205249.Definition: Recovered, restored to healthy condition by natural processes, e.g. by scar formation; freed from illness or injury.

C0205396.Name: Identified
C0205396.Definition: The procedure of having an identity established.

C0035222.Name: Respiratory Distress Syndrome, Adult
C0035222.Definition: Progressive and life-threatening pulmonary distress in the absence of an underlying pulmonary condition, usually following major trauma or surgery. Cases of neonatal respiratory distress syndrome are not included in this definition.

C0019080.Name: Hemorrhage
C0019080.Definition: Bleeding or escape of blood from a vessel.

C0205232.Name: Fine - adjective
C0205232.Definition: Composed of relatively small parts or particles.

C0035868.Name: Rotation
C0035868.Definition: Motion of an object in which either one or more points on a line are fixed. It is also the motion of a particle about a fixed point. (From McGraw-Hill Dictionary of Scientific and Technical Terms, 4th ed)

C0036429.Name: Sclerosis
C0036429.Definition: A pathological process consisting of hardening or fibrosis of an anatomical structure, often a vessel or a nerve.

C0015302.Name: External exotoses
Aliases: ear blockage caused by overgrown bone

C0205039.Name: Bronchial
C0205039.Definition: Of, or pertaining to, the bronchus.

C0205408.Name: Vague
C0205408.Definition: A term that refers to something not explicit or clear in meaning.

C0027627.Name: Neoplasm Metastasis
C0027627.Definition: The transfer of a neoplasm from one organ or part of the body to another remote from the primary site.

C0080103.Name: Relative (related person)
C0080103.Definition: A person related by blood or marriage.

C1522577.Name: follow-up
C1522577.Definition: The process by which information about the health status of an individual is obtained after a study has officially closed; an activity that continues something that has already begun or that repeats something that has already been done.

C0592511.Name: Epidural Route of Drug Administration
C0592511.Definition: Administration of the drug in the epidural space, usually at the lumbar level of the spine. The drug must initially cross the dura mater before exerting its effect on the nervous system components. The drug is also subject to uptake into the rich epidural plexus of veins. Uptake and distribution after epidural administration resembles that seen after intramuscular injection. The portion of drug that is not taken into the vascular compartment is available to cross the dura. Hydrophilicity is a major component in the pharmacokinetics of drug transfer into the subdural space.

C0036525.Name: Metastatic to
C0036525.Definition: A term referring to the clinical or pathologic observation of a tumor extension from its original site of growth to another anatomic site.

C0043240.Name: Wound Healing
C0043240.Definition: Restoration of integrity to traumatized tissue.
Aliases: structure resulting from tissue repair process
structure resulting from tissue repair process (morphologic abnormality)

C0016823.Name: Structure of fundus of eye
C0016823.Definition: The concave interior of the eye, consisting of the retina, the choroid, the sclera, the optic disk, and blood vessels, seen by means of the ophthalmoscope. (Cline et al., Dictionary of Visual Science, 4th ed)
Aliases: structure of fundus of eye (body structure)

C0205173.Name: Double (qualifier value)
C0205173.Definition: Consisting of or involving two parts or components, often in pairs.

C0009368.Name: Colon structure (body structure)
C0009368.Definition: The segment of LARGE INTESTINE between the CECUM and the RECTUM. It includes the ASCENDING COLON; the TRANSVERSE COLON; the DESCENDING COLON; and the SIGMOID COLON.

C0012621.Name: Body Fluid Discharge
C0012621.Definition: The pouring forth of a fluid.

C0205292.Name: Multifocal
C0205292.Definition: Arising from, pertaining to, or having many locations.

C0205182.Name: Atypical
C0205182.Definition: Varying from the norm; not conformable to the type.

C0023928.Name: Lobectomy
C0023928.Definition: Surgical removal of a lobe of an organ.

C0022821.Name: Kyphosis deformity of spine
C0022821.Definition: Deformities of the SPINE characterized by an exaggerated convexity of the vertebral column. The forward bending of the thoracic region usually is more than 40 degrees. This deformity sometimes is called round back or hunchback.

C0004048.Name: Inspiration function
C0004048.Definition: Taking ambient air into the lungs; breathing in.

C0185023.Name: Fixation - action
C0185023.Definition: The act or operation of holding, suturing, or fastening in a fixed position.

C0011923.Name: Diagnostic Imaging
C0011923.Definition: Any visual display of structural or functional patterns of organs or tissues for diagnostic evaluation. It includes measuring physiologic and metabolic responses to physical and chemical stimuli, as well as ultramicroscopy.

C0032320.Name: Pneumoperitoneum
C0032320.Definition: A condition with trapped gas or air in the PERITONEAL CAVITY, usually secondary to perforation of the internal organs such as the LUNG and the GASTROINTESTINAL TRACT, or to recent surgery. Pneumoperitoneum may be purposely introduced to aid radiological examination.

C0242656.Name: Disease Progression
C0242656.Definition: The worsening and general progression of a disease over time. This concept is most often used for chronic and incurable diseases where the stage of the disease is an important determinant of therapy and prognosis.

C0205276.Name: Local
C0205276.Definition: Of or belonging to a restricted area or locality.

C0441635.Name: Anatomical segmentation
C0441635.Definition: One of the parts into which something naturally divides.

C1301886.Name: Diameter (qualifier value)
C1301886.Definition: The length of a straight line passing through the center of a circle or sphere and connecting two points on the circumference.

C0020725.Name: Type II Mucolipidosis
C0020725.Definition: An inherited lysosomal storage disease characterized by the presence of dense intracytoplasmic inclusions in mesenchymal cells, especially fibroblasts. Signs and symptoms include developmental delay, psychomotor deterioration, and growth failure.

C0205419.Name: Variant
C0205419.Definition: An alteration or difference from a norm or standard.

C0205229.Name: Expanding
C0205229.Definition: To increase in size, volume or scope.

C0598782.Name: Appendage
C0598782.Definition: A natural prolongation or projection from a part of an organism either animal or plant; a part that is joined to something larger.

C1522010.Name: Lobar
C1522010.Definition: Of or relating to or affecting a lobe.

C2349954.Name: Withdraw (activity)
C2349954.Definition: To cease active participation in; remove from active use.

C0024202.Name: Lymph
C0024202.Definition: The interstitial fluid that is in the LYMPHATIC SYSTEM.

C0005558.Name: Biopsy
C0005558.Definition: Removal and pathologic examination of specimens from the living body.

C0205341.Name: Repeat
C0205341.Definition: Make or do or perform again.

C0175631.Name: Imagery
C0175631.Definition: visual image which is recalled in accurate detail; mental copy arising from memory of a sense experience in the absence of sensory stimulation.

C0020538.Name: Hypertensive disease
C0020538.Definition: Persistently high systemic arterial BLOOD PRESSURE. Based on multiple readings (BLOOD PRESSURE DETERMINATION), hypertension is currently defined as when SYSTOLIC PRESSURE is consistently greater than 140 mm Hg or when DIASTOLIC PRESSURE is consistently 90 mm Hg or more.
Aliases: complications affecting other specified body systems, not elsewhere classified, hypertension

C0231800.Name: Expiration, function
C0231800.Definition: Expelling modified air from the lungs; breathing out.

C0017596.Name: Glass (substance)
C0017596.Definition: Hard, amorphous, brittle, inorganic, usually transparent, polymerous silicate of basic oxides, usually potassium or sodium. It is used in the form of hard sheets, vessels, tubing, fibers, ceramics, beads, etc.

C1303192.Name: Vertebroplasty
C1303192.Definition: A nonsurgical method for the repair of vertebral fractures and compression due to osteoporosis in which a glue-like material is inserted into the center of the collapsed spinal vertebra in order to stabilize and strengthen the crushed bone.

C0225740.Name: Lingula of left lung
C0225740.Definition: A small tongue-like projection from the lower portion of the upper lobe of the left lung.
Aliases: structure of lingula of left lung
structure of lingula of left lung (body structure)

C0001779.Name: Age
C0001779.Definition: How long something has existed; elapsed time since birth.

C0301559.Name: Screw
C0301559.Definition: medical device used to fix fractured bone

C0524461.Name: Structure of lumen of body system
Aliases: structure of lumen of body system
structure of lumen of body system (body structure)

C0750493.Name: Suspicious
C0750493.Definition: Of a questionable or potentially dangerous nature.

C5200924.Name: Failure
C5200924.Definition: A lack of occurrence or performance.

C0746922.Name: Anatomic Node
C0746922.Definition: Any bulge or swelling of an anatomical structure or part.

C1510467.Name: trauma qualifier
C1510467.Definition: Used with anatomic headings, animals, and sports for wounds and injuries. Excludes cell damage, for which "pathology" is used.

C1707520.Name: Correlation
C1707520.Definition: The degree to which two or more quantities or events are linearly associated, a statistical relation between two or more variables such that systematic changes in the value of one variable are accompanied by systematic changes in the others.

C1522619.Name: Esophageal
C1522619.Definition: Of or relating to the esophagus.

C0489786.Name: Height
C0489786.Definition: The vertical measurement or distance from the base to the top of an object; the vertical dimension of extension.

C0205379.Name: Visible
C0205379.Definition: Perceptible especially by the eye; open to easy view.

C0036277.Name: Bone structure of scapula
C0036277.Definition: Also called the shoulder blade, it is a flat triangular bone, a pair of which form the back part of the shoulder girdle.

C0015357.Name: Extracorporeal Membrane Oxygenation
C0015357.Definition: Application of a life support system that circulates the blood through an oxygenating system, which may consist of a pump, a membrane oxygenator, and a heat exchanger. Examples of its use are to assist victims of SMOKE INHALATION INJURY; RESPIRATORY FAILURE; and CARDIAC FAILURE.

C0015207.Name: Eventration
C0015207.Definition: A localized protrusion of a structure into an adjacent structure or cavity.

C0034866.Name: Recommendation
C0034866.Definition: Advice telling someone what the best thing to do is.

C0030797.Name: Pelvis
C0030797.Definition: The space or compartment surrounded by the pelvic girdle (bony pelvis). It is subdivided into the greater pelvis and LESSER PELVIS. The pelvic girdle is formed by the PELVIC BONES and SACRUM.

C0206427.Name: Rod Photoreceptors
C0206427.Definition: Photosensitive afferent neurons located in the peripheral retina, with their density increases radially away from the FOVEA CENTRALIS. Being much more sensitive to light than the RETINAL CONE CELLS, the rod cells are responsible for twilight vision (at scotopic intensities) as well as peripheral vision, but provide no color discrimination.

C2984009.Name: Suboptimal
C2984009.Definition: Being below an optimal level or standard.

C0021102.Name: Implants
C0021102.Definition: A prosthesis placed permanently in tissue.

C0016169.Name: pathologic fistula
C0016169.Definition: Abnormal communication most commonly seen between two internal organs, or between an internal organ and the surface of the body.

C0443286.Name: Reaction
C0443286.Definition: A response generated by a stimulus.

C0085089.Name: Morphologic artifacts
C0085089.Definition: Any visible result of a procedure which is caused by the procedure itself and not by the entity being analyzed. Common examples include histological structures introduced by tissue processing, radiographic images of structures that are not naturally present in living tissue, and products of chemical reactions that occur during analysis.

C0439639.Name: Wedge
C0439639.Definition: Any shape that is triangular in cross section.

C0742742.Name: Congestive
C0742742.Definition: Relating to or affected by an abnormal collection of blood or other fluid.

C0205391.Name: Widespread
C0205391.Definition: Spread throughout a structure or area.

C2745888.Name: Markers (device)
C2745888.Definition: A medical device designed to mark an anatomic location.

C0456642.Name: Introducer
C0456642.Definition: A component whose function is to facilitate the insertion of a particular device.

C0013812.Name: electrode
C0013812.Definition: Electric conductors through which electric currents enter or leave a medium, whether it be an electrolytic solution, solid, molten mass, gas, or vacuum.

C0302891.Name: Native (qualifier value)
C0302891.Definition: Of or related to the original state or source; natural.

C0007144.Name: Cardia of stomach
C0007144.Definition: That part of the STOMACH close to the opening from ESOPHAGUS into the stomach (cardiac orifice), the ESOPHAGOGASTRIC JUNCTION. The cardia is so named because of its closeness to the HEART. Cardia is characterized by the lack of acid-forming cells (GASTRIC PARIETAL CELLS).
Aliases: the uppermost part of the stomach

C4085887.Name: Inspiratory Vital Capacity Test
C4085887.Definition: The maximum volume of gas an individual can inhale from the point of maximal exhalation.

C1521735.Name: Pectoral
C1521735.Definition: Of or pertaining to the chest.

C0205195.Name: Combined
C0205195.Definition: Made or joined or united into one or involving the joint activity of two or more.

C0205112.Name: Basal
C0205112.Definition: The lowest layer of a structure.

C3828193.Name: September
C3828193.Definition: The ninth month of the year in the Gregorian calendar.

C0013303.Name: Duodenum
C0013303.Definition: The shortest and widest portion of the SMALL INTESTINE adjacent to the PYLORUS of the STOMACH. It is named for having the length equal to about the width of 12 fingers.

C0282443.Name: Review [Publication Type]
C0282443.Definition: An article or book published after examination of published material on a subject. It may be comprehensive to various degrees and the time range of material scrutinized may be broad or narrow, but the reviews most often desired are reviews of the current literature. The textual material examined may be equally broad and can encompass, in medicine specifically, clinical material as well as experimental research or case reports. State-of-the-art reviews tend to address more current matters. A review of the literature must be differentiated from HISTORICAL ARTICLE on the same subject, but a review of historical literature is also within the scope of this publication type.

C0032854.Name: Poverty
C0032854.Definition: A situation in which the level of living of an individual, family, or group is below the standard of the community. It is often related to a specific income level.

C0013931.Name: Embolization, Therapeutic
C0013931.Definition: A method of hemostasis utilizing various agents such as Gelfoam, silastic, metal, glass, or plastic pellets, autologous clot, fat, and muscle as emboli. It has been used in the treatment of spinal cord and INTRACRANIAL ARTERIOVENOUS MALFORMATIONS, renal arteriovenous fistulas, gastrointestinal bleeding, epistaxis, hypersplenism, certain highly vascular tumors, traumatic rupture of blood vessels, and control of operative hemorrhage.

C0037775.Name: Spatial Distribution
C0037775.Definition: The placement, arrangement of instance of entities within a space.

C0178987.Name: Artificial Airways
C0178987.Definition: Devices designed to permit the passage of gases (e.g., air, oxygen) to the lungs while preventing obstruction of the patient's upper airway. These airways include a variety of devices according to the technique used to facilitate the passage of gases, the intended application, and the expected time of use. In emergency and/or for short-time use, esophageal obturation with one- or two-lumen tubes and oropharyngeal artificial airways are typically used. For a few days of intubation, nasopharyngeal artificial airways are the most commonly used devices, while for longer periods (up to three weeks) endotracheal tubes are the preferred devices. When long-term mechanical ventilation is needed, tracheostomy tubes are used. Artificial airways are available in a variety of configurations from newborn to adult sizes.

C0547045.Name: Chronicity
C0547045.Definition: A description or characterization of the duration of a biological process.

C0439751.Name: Entire
C0439751.Definition: Including all components without exception; constituting the full amount or extent or duration; complete.

C0005903.Name: Body Temperature
C0005903.Definition: The measure of the level of heat of a human or animal.

C0011334.Name: Dental caries
C0011334.Definition: Localized destruction of the tooth surface initiated by decalcification of the enamel followed by enzymatic lysis of organic structures and leading to cavity formation. If left unchecked, the cavity may penetrate the enamel and dentin and reach the pulp.

C0180459.Name: Disks (device)
C0180459.Definition: Any device component shaped like a disk, especially those used for data storage.

C3829466.Name: January
C3829466.Definition: The first month of the year in the Gregorian calendar.

C0003850.Name: Arteriosclerosis
C0003850.Definition: Thickening and loss of elasticity of the walls of ARTERIES of all sizes. There are many forms classified by the types of lesions and arteries involved, such as ATHEROSCLEROSIS with fatty lesions in the ARTERIAL INTIMA of medium and large muscular arteries.

C0013798.Name: Electrocardiogram
C0013798.Definition: A study that evaluates the effect of a treatment on cardiac electrical activity, as assessed by electrocardiography.

C0028109.Name: Nipples
C0028109.Definition: The conic organs which usually give outlet to milk from the mammary glands.

C0012725.Name: Psychologic Displacement
C0012725.Definition: The process by which an emotional or behavioral response that is appropriate for one situation appears in another situation for which it is inappropriate.

C0542331.Name: Shunt Device
C0542331.Definition: An implantable device designed to drain fluid from a body cavity.

C0220781.Name: Anabolism
C0220781.Definition: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of substances; typically the energy-requiring part of metabolism in which simpler substances are transformed into more complex ones. [GOC:curators, ISBN:0198547684]

C0205122.Name: Segmental
C0205122.Definition: Having naturally dividable parts; divided into sections with each section adjacent to the other.

C0019409.Name: Heterogeneity
C0019409.Definition: The quality or state of consisting of elements that are not of the same kind or nature.

C0189477.Name: Thoracentesis
C0189477.Definition: Aspiration of fluid or air from the THORACIC CAVITY. It is coupled sometimes with the administration of drugs into the PLEURAL CAVITY.
Aliases: puncture of pleural cavity for aspiration

C3887511.Name: Evidence
C3887511.Definition: Knowledge on which to base belief.

C0546881.Name: Tracking
C0546881.Definition: The act or process of following a person, animal, or object through space or time.

C0441107.Name: Cuffs device
C0441107.Definition: A bandlike device or structure that encircles a body part or another device.

C0521164.Name: Ring (shape)
C0521164.Definition: Doughnut-shaped object or surface generated by rotating a circle around an axis that does not intersect the circle; any object that resembles a ring.

C0018802.Name: Congestive heart failure
C0018802.Definition: Heart failure accompanied by EDEMA, such as swelling of the legs and ankles and congestion in the lungs.

C1696103.Name: image - dosage form
C1696103.Definition: Description:A characteristic representing a single file reference that contains two or more views of the same dosage form of the product; in most cases this should represent front and back views of the dosage form, but occasionally additional views might be needed in order to capture all of the important physical characteristics of the dosage form. Any imprint and/or symbol should be clearly identifiable, and the viewer should not normally need to rotate the image in order to read it. Images that are submitted with SPL should be included in the same directory as the SPL file.

C0006826.Name: Malignant Neoplasms
C0006826.Definition: A tumor composed of atypical neoplastic, often pleomorphic cells that invade other tissues. Malignant neoplasms often metastasize to distant anatomic sites and may recur after excision. The most common malignant neoplasms are carcinomas, Hodgkin and non-Hodgkin lymphomas, leukemias, melanomas, and sarcomas.
Aliases: malignant neoplasm without specification of site

C0184165.Name: Tubing
C0184165.Definition: Small-diameter, hollow cylinders designed for the transfer of materials, typically liquids or gases. These devices may be rigid, semirigid, or flexible; they are typically made of metals, metal alloys, rubber, plastics, or glass with different structures (e.g., one-ply, braided, reinforced) according to the intended use. Tubing is usually available in standardized lengths and in a variety of diameters and wall thicknesses (i.e., gauges) that can be cut into segments of different sizes (i.e., tubes); the tubes may be shaped or modified in other ways (e.g., by attaching connectors) appropriate for a given device and/or application in the healthcare facility (e.g., intravenous fluid administration tubes, laboratory tubes).

C0024881.Name: Mastectomy
C0024881.Definition: Surgical procedure to remove one or both breasts.

C0443246.Name: Left sided
C0443246.Definition: An abnormal transposition to the left side.

C0015811.Name: Femur
C0015811.Definition: The longest and largest bone of the skeleton, it is situated between the hip and the knee.

C0205090.Name: Right
C0205090.Definition: Being or located on or directed toward the side of the body to the east when facing north.

C0231832.Name: Respiratory rate
C0231832.Definition: The rate of breathing (inhalation and exhalation) measured within in a unit time, usually expressed as breaths per minute.

C0058928.Name: ECHO protocol
C0058928.Definition: A chemotherapy regimen consisting of etoposide, vincristine, cyclophosphamide, and doxorubicin that may be used in the treatment of small cell lung cancer (SCLC).
Aliases: etoposide, vincristine, doxorubicin and cyclophosphamide (evac) chemotherapy protocol
cyclophosphamide, doxorubicin, etoposide, and vincristine chemotherapy protocol

C0442120.Name: Intraperitoneal
C0442120.Definition: Relating to the peritoneal cavity as the intended site of administration.

C0012691.Name: Dislocations
C0012691.Definition: Displacement of bones from their normal positions at a joint.

C0020498.Name: Hyperostosis, Diffuse Idiopathic Skeletal
C0020498.Definition: A disease of elderly men characterized by large osteophytes that bridge vertebrae and ossification of ligaments and tendon insertions.

C0476171.Name: Comminuted Fracture type
C0476171.Definition: A fracture in which the bone is splintered or crushed into a number of pieces.

C0205126.Name: Horizontal
C0205126.Definition: Parallel to or in the plane of the horizon.

C0015127.Name: Etiology aspects
C0015127.Definition: Used with diseases for causative agents including microorganisms and includes environmental and social factors and personal habits as contributing factors. It includes pathogenesis.

C0037088.Name: Signs and Symptoms
C0037088.Definition: Clinical manifestations that can be either objective when observed by a physician, or subjective when perceived by the patient.

C1282914.Name: Surrounding (qualifier value)
C1282914.Definition: Extending on all sides of simultaneously; encircling.

C0233494.Name: Tension
C0233494.Definition: A feeling of mental or emotional strain or suspense.

C0347997.Name: Physical object
C0347997.Definition: Something perceptible by one or more of the senses, especially by vision or touch; a material thing.

C0023884.Name: Liver
C0023884.Definition: A large lobed glandular organ in the abdomen of vertebrates that is responsible for detoxification, metabolism, synthesis and storage of various substances.

C0205168.Name: Thin (qualifier value)
C0205168.Definition: Narrow in width, extent or cross-section.

C0205315.Name: Oblique
C0205315.Definition: Slanting or inclined in direction or course or position; neither parallel nor perpendicular nor right-angular.

C0442004.Name: Septal
C0442004.Definition: Of, or related to, or in the direction of, an anatomical septum.

C0031268.Name: Pet Animal
C0031268.Definition: Animals kept by humans for companionship and enjoyment, as opposed to DOMESTIC ANIMALS such as livestock or farm animals, which are kept for economic reasons.

C0205549.Name: Series
C0205549.Definition: A group or succession of objects, substances, or events arranged in regular order in space or time, connected by a like relation, or forming a kind of chain.

C0442045.Name: Visceral
C0442045.Definition: Of, or relating to, or affecting the internal organs.

C0037993.Name: Spleen
C0037993.Definition: An encapsulated lymphatic organ through which venous blood filters.

C0332218.Name: Difficult (qualifier value)
C0332218.Definition: A response indicating that something is or was difficult.

C3495140.Name: Port-A-Cath
C3495140.Definition: A generic term that describes any implantable venous access device that is inserted into a central vein, and connected to a port that can be palpated and accessed for administration of agents and fluid, or for blood sampling.

C0026727.Name: Mucous body substance
C0026727.Definition: The viscous secretion of mucous membranes. It contains mucin, white blood cells, water, inorganic salts, and exfoliated cells.

C0179874.Name: Chamber (physical object)
C0179874.Definition: A component designed as a reservoir/storage.

C0332194.Name: Anterolateral
C0332194.Definition: Denoting the area of the body in front and away from the middle line.

C0006767.Name: Bone callus
C0006767.Definition: The bony deposit formed between and around the broken ends of BONE FRACTURES during normal healing.

C0180860.Name: Filters
C0180860.Definition: A device designed to remove something from whatever passes through it.

C0190165.Name: Annuloplasty
Aliases: reconstruction of annulus of cardiac valve (procedure)
reconstruction of annulus of cardiac valve

C0595836.Name: Intrathoracic Route of Drug Administration
C0595836.Definition: Administration of a drug within the thorax (internal to the ribs).

C0687676.Name: Post
C0687676.Definition: Happening at a time subsequent to a reference time; later in time or order.

C0332255.Name: Fragment of (qualifier value)
C0332255.Definition: A physical quality in which the entity or structure is broken into pieces.

C1522614.Name: Drug Administration via Gastrostomy
C1522614.Definition: Drug administration through a gastric fistula or a surgically created artificial opening into the stomach through the abdominal wall with insertion of a tube.

C0205355.Name: Permanent
C0205355.Definition: Continuing or enduring over time, without fundamental or marked change.

C0205096.Name: Cephalic
C0205096.Definition: Forwards; towards the head or anterior extremity of the body.

C0085198.Name: Esophagectomy
C0085198.Definition: Excision of part (partial) or all (total) of the esophagus. (Dorland, 28th ed)

C0190112.Name: Heart valvuloplasty
C0190112.Definition: Surgery performed for the purpose of repairing a degenerated, calcified, malformed, dysfunctional, etc. heart valve.

C0332768.Name: Joint Subluxations
C0332768.Definition: Partial or incomplete displacement of an articulation.

C0020629.Name: hypopharynx
C0020629.Definition: The bottom portion of the pharynx situated below the OROPHARYNX and posterior to the LARYNX. The hypopharynx communicates with the larynx through the laryngeal inlet, and is also called laryngopharynx.

C0151747.Name: Renal tubular disorder
C0151747.Definition: disease of the kidney structure called tubule

C0443228.Name: Largest
C0443228.Definition: Greatest in size of those under consideration.

C0003893.Name: Arthroplasty
C0003893.Definition: Surgical reconstruction of a joint to relieve pain or restore motion.

C0587267.Name: Closed
C0587267.Definition: Not affording passage or access; blocked against entry.

C0332479.Name: Shapes
C0332479.Definition: The spatial arrangement of something as distinct from its substance.

C0015264.Name: Exertion
C0015264.Definition: Physical or mental energy; hard work.

C5447266.Name: Curly
C5447266.Definition: Curved into nearly a full circle, or coiled. (Makris S, Solomon HM, Clark R, Shiota K, Barbellion S, Buschmann J, Ema M, Fujiwara M, Grote K, Hazelden KP, Hew KW, Horimoto M, Ooshima Y, Parkinson M, Wise LD. Terminology of developmental abnormalities in common laboratory mammals (Version 2). Part B. Birth Defects Res B Dev Reprod Toxicol. 2009 Aug;86(4):227-327.)

C1856053.Name: Hydranencephaly with Renal Aplasia-Dysplasia
C1856053.Definition: A rare genetic lethal multiple congenital anomalies/dysmorphic syndrome with characteristics of severe hydranencephaly and renal dysplasia or agenesis. Pregnancy is complicated by oligo or anhydramnios, leading to features of Potter sequence (including typical facies and microretrognathia, limb contractures, talipes equinovarus, and pulmonary hypoplasia) in the fetus. Affected fetuses either die in utero or shortly after birth. Histology of the brain shows widespread presence of multinucleated neurons and glial cells.
Aliases: multinucleated neurons, anhydramnios, renal dysplasia, cerebellar hypoplasia, hydranencephaly syndrome
multinucleated neurons, anhydramnios, renal dysplasia, cerebellar hypoplasia, and hydranencephaly
multinucleated neurons, anhydramnios, renal dysplasia, cerebellar hypoplasia, hydranencephaly syndrome (disorder)

C0205258.Name: Indeterminate
C0205258.Definition: Cannot distinguish between two or more possible values in the current context.

C0806140.Name: Flow
C0806140.Definition: The continuous movement characteristic of a liquid or gas.

C0376327.Name: International Aspects
C0376327.Definition: An indication that all or part of the research on a grant to a US institution is either conducted in a foreign country, uses foreign subjects or their tissues or medical data, or involves collaboration with foreign researchers.

C0475210.Name: centimeter
C0475210.Definition: A basic unit of length in the former CGS version of metric system, equal to one hundredth of a meter or approximately 0.393 700 787 inch.

C1709367.Name: Oval shape
C1709367.Definition: The shape of either an oval or an ellipse. See also TEAR.

C0034196.Name: Pylorus
C0034196.Definition: The region of the STOMACH at the junction with the DUODENUM. It is marked by the thickening of circular muscle layers forming the pyloric sphincter to control the opening and closure of the lumen.

C0175727.Name: Stimulator
C0175727.Definition: Instruments used to excite (stimulate) functional activities by generating and applying an external agent (e.g., electrical or ultrasonic stimulus). Most stimulators allow for control of the specific duration, intensity, and frequency of the applied stimulus. Stimulators are used for diagnostic, monitoring, functional, therapeutic, experimental, or other purposes, excluding tissue ablation.

C0003873.Name: Rheumatoid Arthritis
C0003873.Definition: A chronic systemic disease, primarily of the joints, marked by inflammatory changes in the synovial membranes and articular structures, widespread fibrinoid degeneration of the collagen fibers in mesenchymal tissues, and by atrophy and rarefaction of bony structures. Etiology is unknown, but autoimmune mechanisms have been implicated.

C0005758.Name: Bulla
C0005758.Definition: Visible accumulations of fluid within or beneath the epidermis.

C0175566.Name: Open
C0175566.Definition: Affording unobstructed entrance and exit; affording free passage or access; accessible to all.

C0028778.Name: Obstruction
C0028778.Definition: Blockage of the normal flow of the contents of an anatomical passageway.

C0019552.Name: Hip structure
C0019552.Definition: The projecting part on each side of the body, formed by the side of the pelvis and the top portion of the femur.

C0151603.Name: Anasarca
C0151603.Definition: A condition that is characterized by the presence of generalized edema. Causes include congestive heart failure, liver failure, renal failure, and severe malnutrition.

C0521378.Name: Biliary
C0521378.Definition: A term that refers to the biliary tract structures.

C0806909.Name: Maximum
C0806909.Definition: The largest possible quantity or degree.

C0000925.Name: Incised wound
C0000925.Definition: A wound or cleft resulted from tissue separation into parts or laid open or penetrated with a sharp edge or instrument.

C0020452.Name: Hyperemia
C0020452.Definition: The presence of an increased amount of blood in a body part or an organ leading to congestion or engorgement of blood vessels. Hyperemia can be due to increase of blood flow into the area (active or arterial), or due to obstruction of outflow of blood from the area (passive or venous).

C0032319.Name: Pneumopericardium
C0032319.Definition: Presence of air or gas in the space between the heart and the PERICARDIUM. The degree of respiratory distress depends on the amount of trapped air and circulation blocked in the systemic and pulmonary veins.

C0024117.Name: Chronic Obstructive Airway Disease
C0024117.Definition: A disease of chronic diffuse irreversible airflow obstruction. Subcategories of COPD include CHRONIC BRONCHITIS and PULMONARY EMPHYSEMA.
Aliases: chronic airway obstruction; not otherwise specified

C0150369.Name: Preventive monitoring
C0150369.Definition: The act of observing something (and sometimes keeping a record of it).

C1293132.Name: Anchoring procedure
C1293132.Definition: Procedure to fix a mobile or flexible structure to a rigid or inflexible structure

C0205157.Name: Remote
C0205157.Definition: Far away in distance or space; happening at a distance.

C0205148.Name: Surface
C0205148.Definition: The extended two-dimensional outer boundary of a three-dimensional object.

C0332306.Name: Quality
C0332306.Definition: An essential and distinguishing attribute of something or someone; a degree or grade of excellence or worth.

C0184898.Name: Surgical incisions
C0184898.Definition: An intentional cut made to an individual's body with the intent of performing a diagnostic or therapeutic intervention.

C0029408.Name: Degenerative polyarthritis
C0029408.Definition: A progressive, degenerative joint disease, the most common form of arthritis, especially in older persons. The disease is thought to result not from the aging process but from biochemical changes and biomechanical stresses affecting articular cartilage. In the foreign literature it is often called osteoarthrosis deformans.
Aliases: osteoarthrosis, unspecified whether generalized or localized

C0012737.Name: Tissue Dissection
C0012737.Definition: The separation and isolation of tissues for surgical purposes, or for the analysis or study of their structures.

C0001527.Name: Adipose tissue
C0001527.Definition: Specialized connective tissue composed of fat cells (ADIPOCYTES). It is the site of stored FATS, usually in the form of TRIGLYCERIDES. In mammals, there are two types of adipose tissue, the WHITE FAT and the BROWN FAT. Their relative distributions vary in different species with most adipose tissue being white.

C0439667.Name: Granulomatous
C0439667.Definition: Relating to or characterized by granulomas.

C0332197.Name: Absent
C0332197.Definition: Not existing in a specified place at a specified time.

C0456904.Name: Intraoperative
C0456904.Definition: Occurring during the course of a surgical procedure.

C0205257.Name: Incomplete
C0205257.Definition: Not whole; lacking some necessary part or detail; unfinished.

C1549092.Name: Antrum
C1549092.Definition: A chamber formation in an organ.

C0442015.Name: Digital X-ray
C0442015.Definition: Acquisition or display of radiographic images using digital techniques; includes digital video fluoroscopy, scan-projection radiography (SPR), digital subtraction and angiography (DSA), digital intravenous angiography (DIVA), and computed tomography. (CRC Dictionary and Handbook of Nuclear Medicine and Clinical Imaging, 1990)

C2700116.Name: Unusual
C2700116.Definition: Out of the ordinary, uncommon, or unexpected.

C0022742.Name: Knee
C0022742.Definition: A region of the lower extremity immediately surrounding and including the KNEE JOINT.
Aliases: bone structure of knee joint region
bone structure of knee joint region (body structure)

C0521440.Name: Epigastric
C0521440.Definition: A locational reference to the mid-upper abdominal area, specifically between the two costal margins and the subcostal plane.

C0205365.Name: Subacute
C0205365.Definition: A disease characteristic falling between acute and chronic, but predominantly acute.

C0026764.Name: Multiple Myeloma
C0026764.Definition: A malignancy of mature PLASMA CELLS engaging in monoclonal immunoglobulin production. It is characterized by hyperglobulinemia, excess Bence-Jones proteins (free monoclonal IMMUNOGLOBULIN LIGHT CHAINS) in the urine, skeletal destruction, bone pain, and fractures. Other features include ANEMIA; HYPERCALCEMIA; and RENAL INSUFFICIENCY.
